To implement sliding doors in a raycasting engine, you’ll need to modify the logic to account for the sliding action. Here’s how you can set it up:

1. Define the Sliding Door Structure
Extend your door structure to include properties for the sliding door, such as position and whether it's opening or closing.

c
Copy code
typedef struct {
    float x;           // Door's starting position
    float y;           // Door's y position
    int is_open;       // 1 for open, 0 for closed
    float target_x;    // Target position when fully open
    float speed;       // Speed of sliding
} SlidingDoor;
2. Update Raycasting Logic
Modify your raycasting function to treat sliding doors differently. When the door is open, it should not block the ray, but when closed, it behaves like a wall.

c
Copy code
int raycast(float rayX, float rayY, SlidingDoor *doors, int num_doors) {
    for (int i = 0; i < num_doors; i++) {
        // Check if the door is closed
        if (!doors[i].is_open) {
            // Check for collision with the closed door
            if (rayX == doors[i].x && rayY == doors[i].y) {
                return 1; // Collision detected
            }
        }
    }
    return 0; // No collision
}
3. Handle Sliding Logic
You’ll need to implement the logic that allows the door to slide open and close. This involves updating its position based on its speed and whether it's currently opening or closing.

c
Copy code
void update_sliding_door(SlidingDoor *door) {
    if (door->is_open) {
        // Slide the door to the open position
        if (door->x < door->target_x) {
            door->x += door->speed; // Move towards open position
            if (door->x >= door->target_x) {
                door->x = door->target_x; // Snap to target position
            }
        }
    } else {
        // Slide the door back to closed position
        if (door->x > door->original_x) {
            door->x -= door->speed; // Move towards closed position
            if (door->x <= door->original_x) {
                door->x = door->original_x; // Snap to original position
            }
        }
    }
}
4. Player Interaction
Handle player interaction to toggle the door's state, causing it to start sliding.

c
Copy code
void toggle_sliding_door(SlidingDoor *door) {
    door->is_open = !door->is_open;
}
5. Rendering the Door
When rendering, draw the door at its current position.

c
Copy code
void render_sliding_door(SlidingDoor *door) {
    // Use door->x and door->y to render the door
    if (door->is_open) {
        // Draw the open state
    } else {
        // Draw the closed state
    }
}
6. Game Loop Integration
In your main game loop, update the doors and check for player interaction:

c
Copy code
int main() {
    SlidingDoor doors[10];
    // Initialize doors with original_x and target_x...
    
    while (game_running) {
        // Handle input...

        // Check for player interaction with sliding doors
        for (int i = 0; i < num_doors; i++) {
            if (player_near_door(player, &doors[i])) {
                if (key_pressed(KEY_E)) {
                    toggle_sliding_door(&doors[i]);
                }
            }
            update_sliding_door(&doors[i]); // Update door position
        }

        // Raycasting
        if (raycast(rayX, rayY, doors, num_doors)) {
            // Collision with a closed door
        }

        // Render doors
        for (int i = 0; i < num_doors; i++) {
            render_sliding_door(&doors[i]);
        }
        
        // Other game logic...
    }
    return 0;
}
Conclusion
This setup provides a basic framework for sliding doors in a raycasting engine. You can enhance it further by adding sounds, visual effects, or animations. Let me know if you have any questions or need more specific help!